
# Heterogeneous Penalties at the Top

Replication and extension of Bach et al. (2018) on heterogeneity in the U.S. residual gender wage gap.

## Authors

- Salma El Aazdoudi
- Rafael Mourouvin
- Maria Micaela Linares Gomez

## Project overview

This repository contains the code and materials for the paper:

**Heterogeneous Penalties at the Top: Glass Ceilings, Hours Convexity, and Motherhood Selection Among Highly Educated Women in the U.S.**

The project replicates the main results of Bach et al. (2018), who use Double Post-Lasso in a high-dimensional framework to document heterogeneity in the U.S. residual gender wage gap, and extends their analysis by focusing on highly educated White non-Hispanic women — the group facing the largest documented penalties.

The original results that OLS substantially understates heterogeneity in the gender wage gap. The extensions then investigate three structural mechanisms behind these penalties.

## Main findings

The project reaches three main conclusions:

- Among highly educated women, the penalty is concentrated at the top of the earnings distribution, consistent with a **glass ceiling**.
- Professional labour markets reward extreme hours convexly, but women working 70+ hours face an additional penalty that offsets this market premium.
- The observed motherhood wage premium among full-time workers is more consistent with **positive selection into employment** than with a causal return to motherhood.

Taken together, the results suggest that highly educated women are held back less by differences in human capital than by the structure of professional labour markets.

